{"id":"1807.04324","submitter":"Klaus Halterman","authors":"Klaus Halterman, Mohammad Alidoust, and Alexander Zyuzin","title":"Epsilon-Near-Zero Response and Tunable Perfect Absorption in Weyl\n  Semimetals","comments":"To be published in Phys. Rev. B","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. B 98, 085109 (2018)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevB.98.085109","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.str-el physics.optics","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We theoretically study the electromagnetic response of type-I and type-II\ncentrosymmetric Weyl semimetals. We derive an anisotropic permittivity tensor\nwith off-diagonal elements to describe such gyrotropic media. Our findings\nreveal that for appropriate Weyl cones tilts, the real part of the transverse\ncomponent of the permittivity can exhibit an epsilon-near-zero response. The\ntilt parameter can also control the amount of loss in the medium, ranging from\nlossless to dissipative when transitioning from type-I to type-II. Similarly,\nby tuning either the frequency of the electromagnetic field or the chemical\npotential in the system, an epsilon-near-zero response can appear as the\npermittivity of the Weyl semimetal transitions between positive and negative\nvalues. Employing the obtained permittivity tensor, we consider a setup where\nthe Weyl semimetal is deposited on a perfect conductive substrate and study the\nrefection and absorption characteristics of this layered configuration. We show\nthat by choosing the proper geometrical and material parameters, devices can be\ncreated that perfectly absorb electromagnetic energy over a wide angular range\nof incident electromagnetic waves.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 11 Jul 2018 19:33:54 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-08-07"}
